<font color="#FF0000">HELP ME UNDERSTAND</font><br>
<tt>Thu Oct 16 14:42:20 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Brothers, I need your help.  I need to talk with you about the thread on the Jolly 365 Crew Returns Home.  I hope one of you might be able to shed some light on a personnal issue that I stuffed back then and is tearing me up at the moment.  I don't want to post over there because it would change the tenure of that thread and I don't want to do that.  What those men did to try and rescue the downed big-wigs deserves its own place. <br><br>
The past 24 hrs have been especially hard for me, and to be honest I am having a hard time seeing the screen right now through the tears, but at least I've stopped screaming and maybe the Paxil is kicking in to do its job and get me out of this emotional flake-out into a more intellectual state of mind.  I can't deal with past questions and responses you left here for me at the moment.  I trust you'll understand.  Thank you for not automatically lumping me in with Barry.  I'm not on-line to kick anybody's butt.  If I look at things differently at times it may be because I believe that if I can not change the situation and it is something that bothers me,  I need to change the way I think about it.  That's back to the old argument is the glass half empty or half full.  The cartoonist Larson went one step further and to the above questions and threw the whole debate into a new level  with  the statement &quot;Hey, I ordered a hamburger not something to drink.&quot; <br><br>
I know I start with a different perspective than most of you,  if I understand correctly from others, in the field your life was the men you served alongside of. Your view would be more of individual trees in a forest than of the forest.   My life was a meeting point seeing individual trees but also a bigger picture where each tree made up the forest.  <br><br>
I was at the 95th in April when this event took place.  We never heard in advance of these secret missions, but within hours after the fact from the men.  These stories from across the border never showed up in the Stars and Stripes because as far as the public was concerned we were staying on our side of the street.  The events of those days are a blur in my mind, you listened to the stories, knew that men were laying down their lives in secret missions to get the first group out, and then we'd send another bunch of guys out to try to rescue the first group and the others who were lost trying to bring them out.    This was so frustrating, and there was nothing we could do about it.  I started wondering how can one man's life be worth so many others.  But as the write up said... those that others were trying to rescue had special knowledge that would be devastating to our side if they were captured.   <br><br>
One day a patient was brought to the hospital, put in his own room away from all the other patients and there was security that I had never seen for other admissions.  There was no record of him being in the hospital.  The military didn't want the word to leak to the VC and anticipated that the enemy would try to capture him if they knew where he had been brought incountry.  Very few people were allowed in to see him.  I had security clearance, and as I said I saw every new admission to the hospital.  I went into the room and spoke with  an older man who was very thin and weak from his ordeal.  At the time I knew his name but as the time passed he was just one of thousands and I forgot who he was but not the incident.  About 2 years ago I pieced together that the man I had talked to, helped get a call through to his wife  and heard of his escape through the river system was Lt. Col. Hambleton.  He had been rescued by some men that I knew from Red Rocks who joked around that the military should have sent them in first.  They had met the challenge and won.<br><br>
I never saw Hambleton again.  I was relieved that he was out of immediate danger from the enemy.  I wish him well and wonder what guilt he bears over the young men that lost their lives in his glorious escape.  The problem I have with the whole situation is why it ever happened in the first place.  WHYWOULD THE MILITARY HAVE ANYONE OVER ENEMY AIR SPACE  SO IMPORTANT THAT THEY WOULD BE WILLING TO RISK ANY NUMBER OF MEN TO GET THEM OUT ?   I have so much free floating anger over this whole incident I could scream.  But the screaming isn't that of rage but frustration.  I cannot adequately  explain how I feel, I don't understand it myself.  <br><br>
Can any of you help me to understand the answer to the question above that haunts me?  WHY?
<p><code>--   (Class Lass) </code><p>


